[h1]The App Delegate Source File[/h1]

The AppDelegate.swift source file has two primary functions.
1. Creating a point of entry and a run loop that delivers input events to your app. This work is carried out by the [b]UIApplicationMain attribute [/b](@UIApplicationMain), which appears toward the top of the file. 
2. Defining the [b]AppDelegate [/b]class, which serves as the blueprint for the app delegate object. The app delegate creates the window where your app's content is drawn, and provides a place to respond to state transitions within the app. The AppDelegate class is where you write your custom app-level code. It contains a single property, [b]window[/b]. [code format="swift"]var window: UIWindow?[/code]
The AppDelegate class also contains templates of important methods. These predefined methods allow the application object to talk to the app delegate.[code format="swift"]func application(application: UIApplication, didFinishLaunchingWithOptions
      launchOptions: [NSObject: AnyObject]?) -> Bool

func applicationWillResignActive(application: UIApplication)

func applicationDidEnterBackground(application: UIApplication)

func applicationWillEnterForeground(application: UIApplication)

func applicationDidBecomeActive(application: UIApplication)

func applicationWillTerminate(application: UIApplication)[/code]
During an app state transition - for example, app launch, transitioning to the background, and app termination - the application object calls the corresponding method in the app delegate, giving it an opportunity to respond appropriately. 
[note]A method templates can also be used to add custom code that will execute when the methods are called.[/note]

[h1]The View Controller Source File[/h1]

Select [b]ViewController.swift[/b] in the project navigator to view it. [img id="999" width="50%"] 
At this point, your [i]ViewController.swift [/i]code should look something like this:[code format="swift"]import UIKit

class ViewController: UIViewController {
    
  override func viewDidLoad() {
     super.viewDidLoad()
  // Do any additional setup after loading the view...
  }
    
}[/code]
[note]Become familiar with the source files. Later on, you'll be writing code into this source code file.[/note]
